{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17641261","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17641261"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:25:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:25:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17875"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17875","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17875"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10589"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115339"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10589","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10589"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17875"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97342"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10069"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24684"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24688"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115339","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115339"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ESkeletal muscle contains significant stores of lipids that play an important role in energy metabolism during exercise.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the metabolism of fatty acids in skeletal muscle?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Fatty acids are stored as intramuscular triglycerides","Fatty acids are released into the circulation","Fatty acids are converted to ketone bodies","Fatty acids are primarily stored as phospholipids","Fatty acids are converted to glucose"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFatty acids are stored as intramuscular triglycerides\u003C/strong\u003E. These triglycerides serve as an important energy reserve that can be mobilised and oxidised within the muscle during prolonged exercise.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFatty acids are released into the circulation\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as unlike adipose tissue, skeletal muscle does not release fatty acids but instead oxidises them internally for energy. \u003Cstrong\u003EFatty acids are converted to ketone bodies\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because ketone body production occurs primarily in the liver, not in skeletal muscle. \u003Cstrong\u003EFatty acids are primarily stored as phospholipids\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect since while phospholipids are present in cell membranes, energy storage occurs as triglycerides. \u003Cstrong\u003EFatty acids are converted to glucose\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as skeletal muscle cannot convert fatty acids to glucose; this occurs only in the liver.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe storage and oxidation of fatty acids within skeletal muscle is crucial for maintaining energy supply during prolonged physical activity.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Skeletal muscle stores fatty acids as intramuscular triglycerides, which serve as an energy source during prolonged exercise.","Fatty acids are oxidised within skeletal muscle cells rather than being released into circulation.","The cycling of fatty acids through storage pools in skeletal muscle is a dynamic process that supports energy metabolism."],"references":["Bender DA, Cunningham SM. Introduction to nutrition and metabolism. CRC Press; 2021.","Salway JG. Metabolism at a Glance. John Wiley \u0026 Sons; 2016.","Chandel NS. Lipid Metabolism. Cold Spring Harb Perspect Biol. 2021 Sep 1;13(9):a040576. doi: 10.1101/cshperspect.a040576. PMID: 34470787; PMCID: PMC8411952.","Wakil SJ, Abu-Elheiga LA. Fatty acid metabolism: target for metabolic syndrome. J Lipid Res. 2009 Apr;50 Suppl(Suppl):S138-43. doi: 10.1194/jlr.R800079-JLR200. Epub 2008 Dec 1. PMID: 19047759; PMCID: PMC2674721."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97342"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17875"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97342","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97342"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-23T12:26:57+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-23T12:26:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10589"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115339"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4931","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4931"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","n